<DOC><DOCNO> AP891009-0201 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-89 2135EDT</FILEID><FIRST>d f AM-ManvilleExpansion     10-09 0179</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Manville Expansion,0185</SECOND><HEAD>Manville Board OKs $65 Million Expansion</HEAD><DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Manville Corp. board on Monday approved a $65million expansion of its fiber glass facility in Waterville, Ohio,which emphasizes its commitment to the reinforcements market, acompany spokesman said.   The project will include the expansion of the fiber glassrovings and chopped strands production, using state-of-the-arttechnology, including some recently licensed technology from NipponElectric Glass of Otsu, Japan, Manville said in a news release.   In February, Manville acquired the exclusive North Americanrights to manufacture chopped strand products using NEG'stechnology. NEG is a leading manufacturer of technical glassproducts for a wide range of industries.   ``We have the technology, the financial resources and thededication of our employees to provide our customers with thehighest quality reinforcement products in the world,'' said RichardA. Kashnow, vice president and general manager of the Denver-basedcompany's mats, fiber and reinforcements division.   Manville is the world's largest producer of fiber glass mats anda leading producer of fiber glass insulation and continuousfilament glass fibers.</TEXT></DOC>